Whenever I make public statements – no matter what I’m actually saying – I follow a whole offensive tyranny on social media, calling for withdrawal, rejection of moderate politics, statements that I don’t belong to the Labour Party.
Like that doesn't happen to just me.
In fact, I know that I was even more fortunate than some of my colleagues, as the comments for me are at least mostly political in nature.
I can only admire the professionalism and purposefulness of those colleagues who face sexist or racist understatements every day without being afraid of them.
One of the biggest disappointments of this era in politics is how such insults became the norm.
Last week, Jeremy Corbyn said Labour should embrace a culture of tolerance.
The reality is that the party is far from wide-ranging, and with every sign of distrust or a change in the rules of choice becomes increasingly narrow.
Over the past two years, I’ve been given a lot of advice not to talk too much and that “everything will be fine.”
But that's not why I went into politics.
Since joining the Labour Party 32 years ago as a student provoked by the Thatcher government, which through its neglect led to the literal disintegration of my excellent school, I have fought for better public services for those who need them most – whether as a local-level adviser or as a minister.
I have never concealed my political views, including during the last election.
No one in Nottingham East could be confused in any way by my political position and my disagreement with the current leadership.
To all those who supported the proposal on Friday, I would like to say that when the state aspires to Brexit, it will hurt households, companies and the public sector, and I do not understand the desire to waste my time and energy in loyalty to the leader of the Labour Party.
But really my message is not to Nottingham Momentum, but to my constituents, whether they are members of the Labour Party or not: I am proud to serve you and I promise that no threat of withdrawal or political exclusion will refuse me to act in the way that I consider to be in your best interest.
