John Edward: Language Skills Are Essential for Global Citizens
Independent schools in Scotland maintain a reputation for academic excellence, continuing in 2018 with another excellent performance of the test scores, which is only enhanced by individual and collective successes in sports, art, music and other social sciences.
With up to 30,000 students across Scotland, these schools, represented by the Scottish Association of Independent Schools (SCIS), strive to offer the best possible level to their students and their parents.
Independent schools aim to prepare their students for their further education, their chosen career, and their place in a global world.
As an educational sector that can compose and implement a personalized curriculum, we see that modern languages continue to be a popular and desirable subject in schools.
Nelson Mandela once said, “If you talk to someone in a language that you can understand, your words can get to him.
But if you speak his own language, you touch his heart.”
It is a powerful reminder that we cannot rely only on the English language when we want to build relationships and trust with the peoples of other countries.
Through the results of this year’s exams, we see that languages are in the first place with the highest success for independent schools.
A total of 68% of students who studied foreign languages achieved a high grade A.
Data collected from 74 SCIS member schools showed that 72% of students had a grade A in Chinese, while the same grade had 72% of German learners, 69% of French learners and 63% of those with Spanish.
This shows that independent schools in Scotland perceive foreign languages as vital skills that children and young people will definitely need for the future.
Currently, languages as subject of free choice by students receive the same treatment as natural-mathematical disciplines (scientific, technological, engineering and mathematical disciplines) both in the programs of independent schools and beyond.
A 2014 study conducted by the UK Employment and Skills Commission found that 17% of employers found that they lacked sufficient language skills because of the reasons why employers find it difficult to find employees.
Therefore, it is becoming increasingly necessary to master foreign languages in order to prepare young people for their future careers.
More and more job positions require mastering a foreign language, which makes these skills essential in a globalized world.
Regardless of the chosen career, if a person masters a foreign language, he will have a real advantage in the future, having mastered such a skill that remains for a lifetime.
The ability to communicate directly with people from other countries automatically puts the multilingual person one breast ahead of the competition.
According to a YouGov survey of more than 4,000 UK adults in 2013, 75% did not speak a foreign language well enough to be able to speak a language, with French being the only language with a two-digit rate of 15%.
That’s why investing in language learning today is important for children now.
Mastering several languages, especially those of developing economies, will provide children with a better chance of finding a good job.
In Scotland, each school will be different from the languages taught.
A number of schools will focus on more classical modern languages, while others will teach languages that are considered to be more important to the UK in a future plan by 2020, such as Chinese or Japanese.
Whatever your child’s interests, there will always be enough languages to choose from in independent schools, with teachers being experts in their field.
Independent schools in Scotland are determined to provide an educational environment that will prepare children and give them the skills they need to succeed in life, no matter what the future holds.
There is no denying that, in a global business environment, languages continue to play an incredibly important role in the future of any country that needs to take this into account in the education system.
And indeed, modern languages should really be considered as “international communication skills”.
Independent schools will continue to offer this choice, along with diversity and excellent quality, to young people in Scotland.
You have to do it right.
John Edward is the Director of the Scottish Association of Independent Schools.
