Harvard students on a course for enough rest
A new course at Harvard University this year leads all students to sleep more in an attempt to combat the growing culture of learning “all night” with the help of caffeine.
A professor found that students at university number one in the world often don’t even think about the very basics of how to take care of themselves.
Charles Keysler, a professor of sleep medicine at Harvard Medical School and a specialist at the Brigham Hospital and Women’s Hospital, prepared the course, which he believes is the first of its kind in the United States.
He was inspired to start the course after talking about the impact of sleep deprivation on learning.
“At last a girl came to me and said, ‘Why are they telling me this until now, in my last year?’
She said that no one had ever told her about the importance of sleep, which surprised me," he told The Telegraph.
The course, which is being held for the first time this year, explains to students the essentials of how good sleep habits help academic and sporting achievement, as well as improving overall well-being.
Paul Bareira, a professor of psychiatry at Harvard Medical School and executive director of the university’s health services, said the university had decided to introduce the course after it was found that students were suffering from a serious lack of sleep during the week.
The one-hour course includes a series of interactive tasks.
In one part, there is an image of a dormitory room where students click on coffee cups, curtains, sneakers, and books to explain the effects of caffeine and light, how sporting achievements are affected by lack of sleep, and the importance of a sleeping routine.
In another part of the study, participants discussed how long-term sleep deprivation can increase the risks of heart attack, stroke, depression, and cancer.
Then a map of the campus with interactive icons encourages participants to think about their daily routine.
“We know that this will not immediately change the behaviour of the students.
But we believe they have a right to know – just as you have a right to know the health effects of choosing to smoke,” added Prof. Kaysler.
The culture of pride in “all-night learning” still exists, he says, adding that modern technologies and the ever-increasing pressure on students mean sleep deprivation is a growing problem.
Providing enough and quality sleep should be the “secret weapon” for students in the fight against stress, exhaustion and anxiety, he says – even to avoid overeating, as sleep deprivation puts the brain into a starvation mode, making them constantly hungry.
Raymond Sow, a 19-year-old student from California who studies chemical and physical biology, helped Professor Keysler prepare the course by taking one of his classes during his first year at Harvard.
He says his course has “opened his eyes” and inspired him to spread it across the campus.
It is hoped that the next step is for all graduate students to be asked to complete a similar curriculum before joining a competitive institution.
Professor Kaysler recommends students to think about setting up a bedtime and wake-up alarm and to know the harmful effects of the “blue light” emitted by electronic screens and LED lighting, which can disrupt the circadian rhythm and lead to problems.
