Yearbook: The Inventor of the Geiger Counter
Page from our yearbook Sunday Morning: September 30, 1882, 136 years ago and BRIEF . . . the day on which the future physicist Johann Wilhelm "Hans" Geiger was born in Germany.
Geiger developed a method for detecting and measuring radioactivity, an invention that ultimately led to the creation of the device known as a Geiger counter.
A cornerstone of science since then, the Geiger counter has also become the cornerstone of pop culture when the 1950 film The Coronado Bells was released, featuring the seemingly incredible scientists Roy Rogers and Dale Evans.
Man: “What, for God’s sake, is this?
Rogers: This is a Geiger counter and is used to detect radioactive minerals, such as uranium.
When you put on these headphones, you can actually hear the effects of the atoms emitted by the radioactivity in the minerals."
Evans: “It certainly matters right now!”
Hans Geiger died in 1945, just days after his 63rd birthday.
But the discovery that bears his name still lives on.
