The inventor of the World Wide Web plans to launch a new Internet to attack Google and Facebook
The inventor of the World Wide Web, Tim Berners-Lee, is starting an enterprise that aims to rival Facebook, Amazon and Google.
The latest project of the technology legend, Inrupt, is a company that builds the open-source platform of Berners-Lee Solid.
Solid allows users to choose where to store their data and which people have permission to access certain information.
In an exclusive interview with Fast Company, Berners-Lee jokes that the intention behind Inrupt is “world domination.”
“We have to do it now,” he said of the venture.
“This is a historic moment.”
The application uses Solid technology, which allows people to create their own “online repository of personal data” or POD.
It contains lists, to-do lists, calendar, music library and other personal and professional tools.
It is similar to Google Drive, Microsoft Outlook, Slack and Spotify, which are accessible through each browser, and at the same time are all of them at the same time.
The unique thing about the online repository of personal data is that the user determines who has access to what information.
The company calls it “Giving Power to Personal Data.”
The idea for Inrupt, according to the company’s CEO John Bruce, is to invest resources, processes and appropriate skills to help Solid become accessible to all.
Currently, the company consists of Burners-Lee, Bruce, a security platform bought by IBM, several developers who signed a contract to work on the project, and a group of volunteer programmers.
From this week, technology developers around the world can create their decentralized applications using the tools available on the Inrupt website.
Berners-Lee said he and his team are not talking to Facebook and Google about whether to make a full change or not when all of their business models are fully updated overnight.
“We don’t want permission from them.”
In a publication in Medium on Saturday, Berners-Lee wrote that Inrupt’s mission is to provide energy for commerce and the ecosystem to help protect the integrity and quality of the new network built on Solid.
In 1994, Berners-Lee transformed the Internet when he created the World Wide Web Consortium at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology.
In recent months, Berners-Lee has had a strong influence on the debate over net neutrality.
Although Inrupt launched, Berners-Lee will remain the founder and director of the World Wide Web Consortium, Web Foundation, and Open Data Institute.
“I’m extremely optimistic about this new era on the Internet,” added Berners-Lee.
Bernard Van: in memory of the priest awarded with the Victoria Cross during the First World War
Celebrating 100 years in the hometown of the only Anglican priest to be awarded the Victoria Cross for his participation in World War I fighting.
Lieutenant Colonel Reverend Bernard Van won the award on 29 September 1918 in the attack of Bellenglise and Lehaucourt.
Four days later, however, he was killed by a sniper without realizing that he had been awarded Britain’s highest military honor.
A memorial was unveiled on Saturday by his two grandchildren at a parade in Rushden, Northamptonshire.
One of his grandsons, Michael Van, said it was "extremely symbolic" that the monument was unveiled exactly 100 years after his grandfather's medal-winning work.
According to the London Gazette on 29 September 1918, Lt. Col. Van led his battalion through the Canal de Saint-Quentin "in a very dense fog and under heavy shelling by artillery and machine guns."
He later attacked the line of fire and led the building forward with "incredible courage" before attacking an artillery cannon with one hand and killing three of the squad.
Lieutenant Colonel Van was killed by a German sniper on October 4, 1918, just a month before the end of the war.
Michael Van, 72, said his grandfather’s actions were “something I know I could never do, but it makes me humble.”
He and his brother Dr. James Van put on a wreath after the parade led by the Brentwood Imperial Youth Band.
Michael Van said it was "a great honor to participate in the parade" and added that "the kindness of the real hero is demonstrated through the support that will be provided to many people."
