Olympic water jumper Tom Daley says he grew up feeling lower than everyone else because of his sexuality — but that’s what motivated him to succeed.
The 24-year-old athlete claims that until he started high school, he didn’t realize that “not everyone is like me.”
In an interview with the first edition of Desert Island Discs on Radio 4, led by Lauren Laverne, he spoke about gay rights to give “hope” to others.
He also said that when he became a parent, he began to be less interested in winning the Olympics.
The permanent host of the long-running show, Kirsty Young, is in hospital for several months.
During his first program, Daley said he felt “less” than anyone else when he was growing up because “it wasn’t socially acceptable to like both girls and boys.”
He said: “To this day, the feeling of inferiority and being different from others are actually the things that give me the energy and strength to succeed.”
He wanted to prove it was “something,” he said, so he wouldn’t disappoint anyone when he finally learned about his sexuality.
The two-time Olympic bronze medalist became an active participant in LGBT campaigns and used his participation in this year’s British Community Games in Australia to call on more countries to decriminalize homosexuality.
He said he does this because he is happy that he can live openly, without consequences, and wants to inspire “hope” for others.
The three-time world champion said when he fell in love with a man — American director Dustin Lance Black, whom he met in 2013 — he was “surprised.”
Dale married the Oscar winner, who is 20 years older than him, last year, but claims the age difference has never been a problem.
"When you're going through so much while you're so young," he first took part in the Olympics at age 14, and his father died of cancer three years later, he said, "it's hard to find someone your age who has experienced such ups and downs."
The two became parents in June and have a son named Robert Ray Black-Daley, and Daley himself says his “whole worldview” has changed.
“If you had asked me last year, I would have told you that I was only interested in winning a gold medal,” he said.
“You know, there are more important things than Olympic gold medals.
"My Olympic gold medal is Robbie."
His son was named after his father Robert, who died in 2011 at the age of 40 after being diagnosed with brain cancer.
Dale said his father could not have accepted that he was going to die and one of the last things he asked was if they already had tickets for the 2012 London Olympics – because he wanted to be in the front row.
“I couldn’t tell him, ‘You’re not going to be with me, Dad, not even in the front row,’” he said.
“I held his hand until he stopped breathing and at that moment, when I found out he was dead, I finally admitted that he was not invulnerable,” he said.
The following year, Daley competed at the 2012 Olympics and won a bronze medal.
“I just knew that my whole life I dreamed of jumping at the Olympics in front of the audience at home. There was no more wonderful feeling,” he said.
This also inspired the choice of his first song – Heather Small’s “Proud” – which accompanied him during his preparations for the Olympics and still makes him squeak.
