Germany postpones the launch of a new warship
The newest frigate of the German fleet was due to be put into operation in 2014 to replace the outdated Cold War battleships, but this will not happen until at least next year due to malfunctioning systems and the massively rising costs, local media reported.
The commissioning of the Rheinland-Pfalz, the brand’s flagship new Baden-Württemberg-class frigates, has been delayed until the first half of 2019, according to the newspaper Die Zeit, which quoted an army spokesman as saying.
The vessel was due to join the naval forces in 2014, but the problems that arose after its delivery affected the fate of the ambitious project.
The four Baden-Wuerttemberg-class ships, commissioned by the Fleet in 2007, will replace the outdated Bremen-class frigates.
It is understandable that they will have a powerful weapon, a set of anti-aircraft and anti-ship missiles, as well as some stealth technologies, such as reduced radar, infrared and acoustic signals.
Other important features include longer maintenance periods – the latest frigates must be able to be used for up to two years before returning to docking ports.
Continuous delays mean, however, that the avant-garde warships — which are said to allow Germany to demonstrate overseas power — will be old when they go into service, Die Zeit notes.
The unfortunate frigate F125 entered the headlines last year when the German Navy officially refused to commission the vessel and returned it to the Blohm & Voss shipyard in Hamburg.
This is the first time the fleet has returned a ship to a shipbuilder after delivery.
Little is known about the reasons for the return, but German media cited a number of significant "software and hardware defects" that make the warship unusable if sent on a combat mission.
The software flaws are particularly important, as the Baden-Wuerttemberg-class vessels will be operated by a crew of around 120 sailors – only half of the crew of the older Bremen-class frigates.
In addition, it turned out that the ship was significantly overloaded, which reduced its efficiency and limited the ability of the navy to add future upgrades.
It is estimated that the 7000-ton "Rheinland-Pfalz" is twice as heavy as the ships of a similar class used by the Germans during World War II.
In addition to the defective hardware, the cost of the entire project – including crew training – also becomes a problem.
It is estimated to have reached a staggering <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>3.1 billion (US$3.6 billion) – out of the initial <0xE2><0x82><0xAC>2.2 billion.
Problems with the newest frigates are becoming especially important in light of recent warnings that Germany’s naval forces are shrinking.
Earlier this year, Hans-Peter Bartels, head of the German Parliament's defence committee, admitted that the fleet was "actually running out of ships capable of carrying out missions."
The official said the problem has grown bigger over time as the old ships have been taken out of service but no new ones have been provided.
He complained that not a single Baden-Württemberg-class frigate could join the fleet.
The National Trust monitors the secret life of bats
A new study, conducted at a mansion in the Scottish mountains, aims to determine how bats use the landscape when hunting.
It is hoped that the findings will shed new light on the behaviour of unique flying mammals and will help guide future conservation actions.
The study by scientists from the National Trust of Scotland will follow the common bats, as well as the brown-eared water bats at Inverewe Gardens in Wester Ross.
Special recording devices will be placed in key locations on the estate to track bat activities during the season.
Employees of the NHS and volunteers will also conduct mobile surveys using manual detectors.
The expert sound analysis of all recordings will determine the frequency of callous sounds of bats, as well as what types they emit.
A habitat map and a report will then be prepared to create a detailed landscape picture of their behavior.
Rob Duar, nature conservation adviser for NTS, hopes the results will reveal which habitat areas are most important for bats and how they are used by each species.
This information will help to determine the benefits of habitat management work, e.g. the creation of meadows, as well as the best way to maintain forest areas for bats and other related species.
Bat populations in Scotland and the UK as a whole have declined significantly in the last century.
They are threatened by construction activities that affect their shelters and lead to the loss of habitats.
A risk to populations can be from wind turbines and lighting, aircraft and some chemical processing of building materials, as well as attacks by domestic cats.
In fact, bats are not blind.
However, due to their hunting habits at night, their ears are more useful than their eyes when it comes to catching prey.
They use advanced echolocation techniques to detect insects and obstacles along their flight paths.
NTS, which is responsible for the care of more than 270 historic buildings, 38 gardens of great importance and 76,000 hectares of land in the country, takes bats very seriously.
The Trust has trained experts who conduct regular surveys, inspections of shelters and sometimes rescue operations.
The organisation has even created the first in Scotland and the only special butterfly reserve in the Threeave Manor in the Dumfries and Galloway area, which is home to eight of the ten species of butterflies in Scotland.
The landlord, David Thompson, says it's the perfect territory for them.
“Here at Threave, we have a great terrain for bats,” he said.
“We have old buildings, a lot of mature trees and a completed suitable habitat.
But there are still a lot of things about bats that aren’t known, so the work we do here and in other properties will help us better understand what they need to thrive.”
He stressed that it is important to check for bats before real estate maintenance activities are carried out, as it is possible that the unintentional destruction of a shelter would kill up to 400 female and young bats, as well as destroy an entire local population.
Bats are a protected species and it is illegal to kill, harass, disturb or destroy their shelters.
Elizabeth Ferrell, a Scottish employee at the Bat Conservation Trust, encouraged the community to help.
She said: “I still have a lot to learn about our bats and many of our animal species, because we just don’t know what’s going on with their populations.”
