Brexit: Britain 'will forever regret' losing car makers
Britain “will regret it forever” if it loses its status as a world leader in post-Brexit car manufacturing, Business Secretary Greg Clark said.
He added that it was “concerning” that Toyota UK had told the BBC that if the UK leaves the EU without a deal, it would temporarily halt production at its plant in Burnaston, near Derby.
“We need a deal,” he said.
The Japanese carmaker said the impact of a no-deal Brexit delay could lead to job losses.
Nearly 150,000 vehicles were produced at the Burnaston plant – where the Auris and Avensis models are manufactured – last year, 90% of which were exported to the rest of the European Union.
“My opinion is that if the UK leaves the EU at the end of March, production at our plant will stop,” said Marvin Cook, Toyota’s director at Burnston.
Other UK carmakers, including Honda, BMW and Jaguar Land Rover, have voiced concerns about leaving the EU without an agreement and how cross-border trade will work.
BMW, for example, says it will close its plant for the Mini in Oxford a month after Brexit.
The main concerns of car manufacturers are related to the risks to the supply chain in the case of a no-deal Brexit.
Toyota’s production line works on a “just in time” basis, with parts arriving every 37 minutes from suppliers from both the UK and the EU for custom-made cars.
If the UK leaves the EU without a deal on March 29, there could be problems at the border, which the industry says could lead to delays and shortages of parts.
It would be impossible for Toyota to wait more than a day to replenish its inventory at the Darbyshire plant, the company said, and therefore production will stop.
Mr Clarke said Theresa May’s “chess” plan for future relations with the EU was “precisely calibrated to avoid these border checks.”
“We need to have a deal. We want to make the best deal that will allow us, as I say, not only to enjoy the current success, but also to be able to seize that opportunity,” he said on BBC Radio’s 4’s Today programme.
“Following the claims not only of Toyota, but also of other manufacturers, we are absolutely convinced that we must be able to continue to provide successful supply chains.”
Toyota cannot say for how long production will be halted, but in the longer term they warn that the additional costs will reduce the competitiveness of the plant and ultimately lead to the loss of jobs.
Peter Cuvalaris, who has been working in Burnaston for 24 years and is the founder of the Unite union at the plant, said his members were increasingly concerned: “From my experience, I judge that if these jobs go away, they will never come back.
A government spokesman said: “We have put forward a precise and reliable plan for our future relations with the EU.”
Trump-Rosenstein meeting could be postponed again, White House says
Donald Trump’s crucial meeting with Deputy Attorney General Rod Rosenstein could be “delayed by another week” as Supreme Court candidate Brett Kavanaugh’s fight continues, the White House said on Sunday.
Rosenstein oversees the work of Special Adviser Robert Mueller, who is investigating Russian interference in the election, links between Trump aides and Russia, and potential impediments to justice on the part of the president.
