Theresa May will announce today the decision for foreign buyers to pay a higher coat of arms tax on the purchase of real estate in the UK, with additional revenue going to help homeless people.
This move will be seen as an attempt to neutralize the success of Jeremy Corbyn’s efforts to attract young voters by promising more affordable housing and targeting high-income people.
The increase in the coat of arms tax will affect individuals and companies that do not pay taxes in the UK, and the additional revenue will help the government’s efforts to limit the number of people sleeping on the street.
The supplement – which is an addition to the current coat of arms tax, including the higher levels introduced two years ago for second homes and properties purchased for the purpose of bestowal – can amount to up to three percent.
The Treasury expects revenues to increase by up to <0xC2><0xA3>120 million per year.
About 13 percent of newly built buildings in London are purchased by people with citizenship outside the UK, which leads to higher prices and makes it difficult for people who buy property for the first time to interfere in the real estate market.
Many of the rich areas – especially in the capital – have become “ghost cities” because of the large number of foreign buyers who spend most of their time outside the country.
The new policy comes just weeks after Boris Johnson asked for a reduction in the coat of arms tax to help more young people own their first home.
He accused major construction companies of maintaining high property prices by plundering land but not using it, and asked Ms May to abandon quotas for affordable housing to fix Britain’s “home disgrace.”
Mr. Corbyn announced an attractive series of proposals for housing reforms, including rent control and an end to "no-wine" evictions.
He also wants to give councils greater powers to build new homes.
Mrs May said: “Last year I shared that I would like to dedicate my time as Prime Minister to restoring the British dream of a better life for every new generation.
