The first shots in the trade war between the U.S. and China were deafening, and while the battle is still gaining momentum, a rift between the two countries will benefit Beijing in the long run, experts say.
U.S. President Donald Trump launched the first warning salvo this year, taxing key elements of China’s exports, including solar panels, steel and aluminum.
The biggest escalation of tensions came this week with new tariffs affecting production of US$200 billion (<0xC2><0xA3>150 billion) with effective taxation of half of all goods imported into the US from China.
Each time, Beijing countered new tariffs with five to ten percent of U.S. goods for $60 billion.
China has vowed to respond to every U.S. strike, and the world’s second-largest economy is not expected to ignore it anytime soon.
To make Washington give up is to yield to demands, but to make a public statement to Washington would be too embarrassing for Xi Jinping, the president of China.
Yet, experts say, if Beijing plays its cards right, the pressure from the trade war with the US could help China in the long run by reducing the interdependence of the two economies.
“The fact that a hasty political decision in both Washington and Beijing could create the conditions for an economic crisis in either country is actually more dangerous than observers have admitted before,” said Abigail Grace, an American security researcher at the Center’s expert group.
Syria is ‘ready’ for refugees to return, foreign minister says
Syria has announced that it is ready for the voluntary return of refugees and is asking for assistance in the reconstruction of the country devastated by the war that has lasted for more than seven years.
In an address to the UN General Assembly, Foreign Minister Walid al-Mualem stressed that conditions in the country are improving.
"Today, the situation on the ground is more stable and safe, thanks to the progress we have made in the fight against terrorism," he said.
The government continues to restore the areas devastated by the terrorists to return them to their normal state.
There are now all conditions for the voluntary return of refugees to the country they were forced to leave because of terrorism and the unilateral economic measures that affected their daily lives and livelihoods.
The UN estimates that more than 5.5 million Syrians have left the country since the start of the war in 2011.
Another six million people still living there are in need of humanitarian assistance.
Al-Mualem said the Syrian regime would welcome any help in restoring the devastated state.
But he stressed that conditional aid or assistance from countries that financed the rebels would not be accepted.
