New to Red Tide: Concentrations Decrease in Pinelas, Manuti and Sarasota
The latest report of the Committee on Fish and Wildlife in Florida shows a fundamental reduction in red-tidal concentrations in areas of Tampa Bay.
According to the Committee, there are reports of conditions of growth disruption in the areas of Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Charlotte and Collier counties – this shows a decrease in concentrations.
Excessively blooming areas of the red tide stretch approximately 130 miles along the coast, from the northern Pinellas County to the southern Lee County.
Plots of algae can be seen 10 miles off the coast of Hillsboro County, but are smaller than last week.
Red tide is also observed in Pasco County.
In the past week, there have been reports of moderate concentrations in the coastal zone or a little further inland in the county of Pinelas, low to high concentrations along the coast of Hillsboro County, conditions for high concentrations in Manotti County, conditions for high concentrations in the county of Manotti, conditions for high concentrations in the county of Manotti.
Inflammation of the airways continues to be reported in Pinelas, Manotti, Sarasota, Lee and Collier counties.
There have been no reports of airway inflammation in Northwest Florida in the past week.
